 961: Create/update `docs/API-SCHEMA-ORG.md`:
 962: 
 963: ```markdown
 964: # API Reference - Schema.org Integration
 965: 
 966: ## Overview
 967: 
 968: All calendar event endpoints return responses with embedded schema.org structured data for semantic web compatibility.
 969: 
 970: ## Event Endpoints
 971: 
 972: ### POST /mcp/tools - create-event
 973: 
 974: Creates a new calendar event with schema.org metadata.
 975: 
 976: **Request**:
 977: ```bash
 978: {
 979:   "name": "create-event",
 980:   "arguments": {
 981:     "calendarId": "primary",
 982:     "summary": "Team Meeting",
 983:     "start": "2026-03-24T10:00:00",
 984:     "end": "2026-03-24T11:00:00",
 985:     "location": "Room 101",
 986:     "description": "Quarterly planning meeting",
 987:     "attendees": ["alice@example.com", "bob@example.com"]
 988:   }
 989: }
 990: ```
 991: 
 992: **Response**:
 993: ```json
 994: {
 995:   "content": [{
 996:     "type": "text",
 997:     "text": "{
 998:       \"event\": { /* Google Calendar event */ },
 999:       \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\",
1000:       \"@type\": \"Event\",
1001:       \"identifier\": \"abc123\",
1002:       \"name\": \"Team Meeting\",
1003:       \"startDate\": \"2026-03-24T10:00:00-07:00\",
1004:       \"endDate\": \"2026-03-24T11:00:00-07:00\",
1005:       \"location\": \"Room 101\",
1006:       \"description\": \"Quarterly planning meeting\",
1007:       \"attendee\": [
1008:         { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"email\": \"alice@example.com\" },
1009:         { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"email\": \"bob@example.com\" }
1010:       ]
1011:     }"
1012:   }]
1013: }
1014: ```
1015: 
1016: **Schema.org Properties**:
1017: - `@context`: Always `https://schema.org`
1018: - `@type`: Always `Event`
1019: - `identifier`: Event ID (string, unique per calendar)
1020: - `name`: Event summary/title
1021: - `startDate`: ISO 8601 with UTC offset
1022: - `endDate`: ISO 8601 with UTC offset
1023: - `location`: Event location (string)
1024: - `description`: Event description
1025: - `attendee`: Array of Person objects
1026: 
1027: ### GET /mcp/tools - get-event
1028: 
1029: Retrieves a specific event with schema.org metadata.
1030: 
1031: **Request**:
1032: ```bash
1033: {
1034:   "name": "get-event",
1035:   "arguments": {
1036:     "calendarId": "primary",
1037:     "eventId": "abc123"
1038:   }
1039: }
1040: ```
1041: 
1042: **Response**: Same as create-event response
1043: 
1044: ### GET /mcp/tools - list-events
1045: 
1046: Lists events with schema.org metadata for each event.
1047: 
1048: **Response**:
1049: ```json
1050: {
1051:   "content": [{
1052:     "type": "text",
1053:     "text": "[
1054:       {
1055:         \"event\": { /* first event */ },
1056:         \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\",
1057:         \"@type\": \"Event\",
1058:         /* schema.org properties */
1059:       },
1060:       {
1061:         \"event\": { /* second event */ },
1062:         \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\",
1063:         \"@type\": \"Event\",
1064:         /* schema.org properties */
1065:       }
1066:     ]"
1067:   }]
1068: }
1069: ```
1070: 
1071: ### Other Endpoints
1072: 
1073: - `update-event`: Same schema.org response format
1074: - `search-events`: Returns array of events with schema.org metadata
1075: - `delete-event`: Returns success status (no schema.org Event needed)
1076: 
1077: ## Validation
1078: 
1079: All responses can be validated with the [Schema.org JSON-LD Validator](https://validator.schema.org/).
1080: 
1081: ## Migration Guide
1082: 
1083: ### For Existing Clients
1084: 
1085: **No changes required.** All existing code continues to work:
1086: 
1087: ```typescript
1088: // Old code still works - get event from 'event' property
1089: const event = response.event;
1090: const title = event.summary;
1091: const start = event.start.dateTime;
1092: ```
1093: 
1094: ### For New Clients
1095: 
1096: Use schema.org properties for structured data:
1097: 
1098: ```typescript
1099: // New code can use schema.org properties
1100: const title = response.name;
1101: const start = response.startDate;
1102: const end = response.endDate;
1103: const attendees = response.attendee?.map(p => p.email);
1104: ```
1105: 
1106: ## Timezone Handling
1107: 
1108: All `startDate` and `endDate` values are ISO 8601 with UTC offset:
1109: 
1110: ```
1111: Input:  { dateTime: "2026-03-24T10:00:00", timeZone: "America/Los_Angeles" }
1112: Output: "2026-03-24T10:00:00-07:00"
1113: ```
1114: 
1115: For all-day events (no time component):
1116: 
1117: ```
1118: Input:  { date: "2026-03-24" }
1119: Output: "2026-03-24"
1120: ```
1121: ```
