  6: This guide provides the exact MCP tool calls needed to retrieve and validate schema.org type definitions for the Google Calendar MCP codebase.
  7: 
  8: ---
  9: 
 10: ## Quick Start: Run All Tools
 11: 
 12: The following commands retrieve complete schema.org definitions for the main codebase types:
 13: 
 14: ### Core Schema Tools (5 tools)
 15: 
 16: #### 1️⃣  `get_schema_type` - Retrieve "Event" type definition
 17: 
 18: **Purpose**: Get complete Event type with all properties, inheritance, and documentation
 19: 
 20: ```json
 21: {
 22:   "name": "get_schema_type",
 23:   "arguments": {
 24:     "typeName": "Event"
 25:   }
 26: }
 27: ```
 28: 
 29: **Expected Output Structure**:
 30: - `@id`: https://schema.org/Event
 31: - `@type`: rdfs:Class
 32: - `rdfs:label`: "Event"
 33: - `rdfs:comment`: Full documentation
 34: - `rdfs:subClassOf`: Parent types (Thing → CreativeWork → Event)
 35: - `properties[]`: Array of all Event properties (name, startDate, endDate, location, attendee, organizer, etc.)
 36: 
 37: **Why**: Event is the primary mapping target for CalendarEvent interface
 38: 
 39: ---
 40: 
 41: #### 2️⃣  `search_schemas` - Find calendar-related types
 42: 
 43: **Purpose**: Discover all schema.org types related to calendars and scheduling
 44: 
 45: ```json
 46: {
 47:   "name": "search_schemas",
 48:   "arguments": {
 49:     "query": "calendar",
 50:     "limit": 10
 51:   }
 52: }
 53: ```
 54: 
 55: **Expected Results**:
 56: - Calendar (type for calendar collections)
 57: - CalendarSlot (if available)
 58: - Schedule (time availability)
 59: - EventSeries (recurring events)
 60: 
 61: ---
 62: 
