 49: ## Quick Start
 50: 
 51: ### Prerequisites
 52: 
 53: 1. A Google Cloud project with the Calendar API enabled
 54: 2. OAuth 2.0 credentials (Desktop app type)
 55: 
 56: ### Google Cloud Setup
 57: 
 58: 1. Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com)
 59: 2. Create a new project or select an existing one.
 60: 3. Enable the [Google Calendar API](https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/calendar-json.googleapis.com) for your project. Ensure that the right project is selected from the top bar before enabling the API.
 61: 4. Create OAuth 2.0 credentials:
 62:    - Go to Credentials
 63:    - Click "Create Credentials" > "OAuth client ID"
 64:    - Choose "User data" for the type of data that the app will be accessing
 65:    - Add your app name and contact information
 66:    - Add the following scopes (optional):
 67:      - `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events` and `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar`
 68:    - Select "Desktop app" as the application type (Important!)
 69:    - Save the auth key, you'll need to add its path to the JSON in the next step
 70:    - Add your email address as a test user under the [Audience screen](https://console.cloud.google.com/auth/audience)
 71:       - Note: it might take a few minutes for the test user to be added. The OAuth consent will not allow you to proceed until the test user has propagated.
 72:       - Note about test mode: While an app is in test mode the auth tokens will expire after 1 week and need to be refreshed (see Re-authentication section below).
